    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what do you mean by goblin? lol i'm just trying to understand the legal part of how the money moves. is it a person or a bank? and what exactly are the \"rules\" you mentioned that they check?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the goblin! The goblin is the metaphorical name for the **escrow agent**, a licensed professional who acts as the neutral referee in this high-stakes game. In Toronto, this isn't just a random person; it's usually a specialized **title company** or a **trust company** (like Great-West Life or a local title insurer) that operates under strict legal statutes. They aren't just \"holding\" money; they are legally bound to follow a specific **escrow agreement** that dictates exactly when funds move and when documents are released.\n\nThe \"rules\" you mentioned are the **conditions precedent** listed in your purchase agreement. Think of these as the goblin's checklist before letting anyone leave the vault:\n1.  **Clear Title:** The goblin must verify the seller has no hidden debts or liens (like a goblin hiding a cursed coin).\n2.  **Inspections:** Did the buyer pass the home inspection? If the house has a goblin-sized leak, the deal might stall.\n3.  **Financing:** Has the buyer's bank approved the loan? If the goblin sees the buyer's credit score is too low, the vault stays locked.\n4",
